BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:XBijgkgRipT8mSG-i3FVp
SUMMARY:Beyond Mysticism: The Modern Northwest
DTSTAMP:20260404T043958Z
DTSTART:20260411T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:image: Drift No. 2\, 1936\, Malcolm M. Roberts\, American\, 191
	3-1990\, tempera on board\, 25 1/2 x 20 5/8 in.\, Seattle Art Museum\, Eug
	ene Fuller Memorial Collection\, 37.103\, © Malcolm M. Roberts\, photo: Sc
	ott Leen.\n\nInspired by the region’s natural beauty and rapidly changing 
	city\, this exhibition showcases artists who told the raw story of Seattle
	 in the 20th century. By sharing the Pacific Northwest’s perspective throu
	gh trending art styles—including Social Realism\, Surrealism\, and Abstrac
	t Expressionism—these artists offered a unique take on Modernist art and c
	hallenged the “mystic” label ascribed to their works.\n\nSpearheading the 
	movement were local icons Mark Tobey\, Kenneth Callahan\, Guy Anderson\, a
	nd Morris Graves—but the range and breadth of Pacific Northwest art goes b
	eyond the “Big Four” of the Northwest School. Featuring more than 150 piec
	es\, this exhibition showcases works that investigate the complexities of 
	daily life in the region. Whether applying an ecocritical lens or producin
	g dreamy and uncanny visuals\, these artists expressed the duality of the 
	natural world and city life to warn of the environmental and social impact
	s of industrialization.\n\nFrom Malcolm Roberts to Kenjiro Nomura\, learn 
	how Northwest artists applied their regional perspective to broader artist
	ic developments to create a new form of American Modernism.\n\nThe exhibit
	ion is accompanied by a fully illustrated catalogue authored by Theresa Pa
	panikolas\, SAM’s Ann M. Barwick Curator of American Art.\n\nhttps://seato
	day.6amcity.com/events/#/details/beyond-mysticism-the-modern-northwest/183
	08126/2026-04-11T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - All Events
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/beyond-mysticism-the-mode
	rn-northwest/18308126/2026-04-11T00
LOCATION:Seattle Art Museum\, 1300 First Avenue\, Seattle\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-all
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - All Events
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:almeyMCAtztQ3DyiVo8WL
SUMMARY:Homebuyer Education Workshop
DTSTAMP:20260404T043958Z
DTSTART:20260411T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:This is a free five-hour workshop to help you meet the WA State
	 Housing Finance Commission’s education requirements for down payment assi
	stance and a variety of affordable housing programs and opportunities for 
	qualified applicants! These requirements include the successful completion
	 of a Homebuyers Education Seminar meeting the current FHA\, Fannie Mae\, 
	FreddieMac\, and SMBA benchmark standards.  \n\nAt the conclusion of the w
	orkshop\, participants will receive a certificate of achievement from the 
	WA State Housing Finance Commission and DFI valid for two years from the d
	ate of issuance.  \n\nTo join our next workshop\, please complete and subm
	it the following registration form at least 24-hours before your selected 
	workshop date. Once this form has been submitted\, be sure to check your e
	mail for a digital confirmation\, as well as additional follow up and impo
	rtant information from a ULMS Housing Department staff member.   \n\nIn-pe
	rson workshops are held every 1st and 2nd Saturday of the month from 10:00
	AM – 3:30PM. They will be held at our Main Office at the following address
	: 105 14th Ave\, Suite 200 Seattle\, WA 98122.\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity
	.com/events/#/details/homebuyer-education-workshop/17282958/2026-04-11T00\
	n\nFrom SEAtoday - All Events
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/homebuyer-education-works
	hop/17282958/2026-04-11T00
LOCATION:ULMS\, 105 14th Avenue\, Suite 200\, Seattle\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-all
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - All Events
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT5H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:w7PBVoA7VB8NZz-SMXFYf
SUMMARY:Foraging for Basketry and Wild Crafts
DTSTAMP:20260404T043958Z
DTSTART:20260411T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:Taught by basket maker and teacher Erin Cox. Join the conversat
	ion about the incredible plants that grow here in the Pacific Northwest an
	d explore ways to identify\, gather\, store and use them to create baskets
	 and crafts that bring nature inside. Whether you live in an urban\, subur
	ban or rural setting\, there are forage-able crafting and weaving material
	s to be found. Daylily\, daffodil\, dandelion\, crocosmia\, iris\, cattail
	s\, juncus\, bulrush\, ivy\, honeysuckle\, wisteria\, dogwood\, willow and
	 more! Erin will share about her approach to sustainable and responsible f
	oraging. We should all care for the plants we harvest and preserve the env
	ironments they grow in. This discussion is good for beginners and you will
	 walk away with some fun\, easy ways to get started. $17.50 BBGS Member/$2
	5 Non-Member \n\nErin found her life’s passion in basketry and wild crafti
	ng. In 2024 she established a small basketry willow farm in Carnation\, Wa
	shington\, where she invites students to learn\, harvest\, and engage with
	 the materials. In 2025\, she opened Field and Forest Crafts and her own p
	rivate teaching studio in NE Seattle.\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.com/even
	ts/#/details/foraging-for-basketry-and-wild-crafts/18185398/2026-04-11T00\
	n\nFrom SEAtoday - All Events
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/foraging-for-basketry-and
	-wild-crafts/18185398/2026-04-11T00
LOCATION:Bellevue Botanical Garden\, 12001 Main St\, Bellevue\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-all
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - All Events
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT2H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:Itejab1FgjMaedihHY9K5
SUMMARY:TADAIMA: I'm Home
DTSTAMP:20260404T043958Z
DTSTART:20260411T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:After more than 80 years\, a treasured collection returns “home
	” to Seattle’s Japanese American community. In 1942 dozens of traditional 
	Boys’ and Girls’ Day dolls were entrusted to Bailey Gatzert Elementary Sch
	ool by Japanese American families facing forced incarceration. Most were n
	ever reclaimed after the war. Artist Miya Sukune uses recent research in M
	OHAI’s collection\, as well as interviews with Japanese American survivors
	 and their descendants\, to create an installation called “Tadaima\,” mean
	ing “I’m home.”\n\nTADAIMA: “I’m Home!” Bringing Seattle’s Girls’ and Boys
	’ Day Dolls Home reconnects the dolls with their traditional role of prote
	cting and blessing children. It invites visitors to celebrate the resilien
	ce\, memory\, and enduring traditions of the Japanese American Community.\
	n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/tadaima-i-m-home/18096356
	/2026-04-11T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - All Events
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/tadaima-i-m-home/18096356
	/2026-04-11T00
LOCATION:Museum of History and Industry\, 860 Terry Ave N\, Seattle\, Seatt
	le\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-all
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - All Events
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
