BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:szWxAprAKe8GhA6j-LZ77
SUMMARY:Moomins' Sea Adventures & Tove and the Sea
DTSTAMP:20260404T043959Z
DTSTART:20260416T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:Dive into the whimsical world of Moominvalley and the life of i
	ts creator\, Tove Jansson\, with *Moomins’ Sea Adventures* and *Tove and t
	he Sea*.\n\n*Moomins’ Sea Adventures* brings Moominvalley to life with ill
	ustrations and life-sized characters from the stories. In the center of th
	e exhibit is an interactive island complete with a lighthouse and rowboats
	 that invites visitors to imagine adventures of their own.\n\n*Tove and th
	e Sea* offers a more intimate counterpoint\, tracing Tove Jansson’s lifelo
	ng relationship with the Finnish archipelago through large-scale photograp
	hs and reflective texts.\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/
	moomins-sea-adventures-tove-and-the-sea/18406909/2026-04-16T00\n\nFrom SEA
	today - All Events
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/moomins-sea-adventures-to
	ve-and-the-sea/18406909/2026-04-16T00
LOCATION:National Nordic Museum\, 2655 NW Market Street\, Seattle\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-all
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - All Events
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:fUPYSFbh2hG3cvJquI9zg
SUMMARY:Figure/Ground: New Criteria
DTSTAMP:20260404T043959Z
DTSTART:20260416T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:Figure/Ground: New Criteria is inspired by cultural historian S
	arah Lewis’s concept of “groundwork aesthetics\,” exploring figure-ground 
	relationships and their connection to social tension. It builds on Lewis’s
	 work\, which—set against the expansion of Stand Your Ground laws across t
	he United States since 2005\, laws that broadly define rights to use letha
	l self-defense against perceived threats—describes a range of artistic int
	erventions that reimagine “the literal and figurative meaning of ground.” 
	Primarily featuring works from the Henry collection created in the twenty-
	first century\, Figure/Ground reflects a period in which hard-won civil ri
	ghts and claims to self-determination have been eroded across the US\, dis
	proportionately affecting Black\, Brown\, LGBTQ\\+\, and other marginalize
	d communities.\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/figure-gro
	und-new-criteria/17923441/2026-04-16T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - All Events
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/figure-ground-new-criteri
	a/17923441/2026-04-16T00
LOCATION:Henry Art Gallery\, 15th Ave NE & 41st St\, Seattle\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-all
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - All Events
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT9H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:CFHYxiw_raOgOwNv5JocO
SUMMARY:Beyond Mysticism: The Modern Northwest
DTSTAMP:20260404T043959Z
DTSTART:20260416T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:image: Drift No. 2\, 1936\, Malcolm M. Roberts\, American\, 191
	3-1990\, tempera on board\, 25 1/2 x 20 5/8 in.\, Seattle Art Museum\, Eug
	ene Fuller Memorial Collection\, 37.103\, © Malcolm M. Roberts\, photo: Sc
	ott Leen.\n\nInspired by the region’s natural beauty and rapidly changing 
	city\, this exhibition showcases artists who told the raw story of Seattle
	 in the 20th century. By sharing the Pacific Northwest’s perspective throu
	gh trending art styles—including Social Realism\, Surrealism\, and Abstrac
	t Expressionism—these artists offered a unique take on Modernist art and c
	hallenged the “mystic” label ascribed to their works.\n\nSpearheading the 
	movement were local icons Mark Tobey\, Kenneth Callahan\, Guy Anderson\, a
	nd Morris Graves—but the range and breadth of Pacific Northwest art goes b
	eyond the “Big Four” of the Northwest School. Featuring more than 150 piec
	es\, this exhibition showcases works that investigate the complexities of 
	daily life in the region. Whether applying an ecocritical lens or producin
	g dreamy and uncanny visuals\, these artists expressed the duality of the 
	natural world and city life to warn of the environmental and social impact
	s of industrialization.\n\nFrom Malcolm Roberts to Kenjiro Nomura\, learn 
	how Northwest artists applied their regional perspective to broader artist
	ic developments to create a new form of American Modernism.\n\nThe exhibit
	ion is accompanied by a fully illustrated catalogue authored by Theresa Pa
	panikolas\, SAM’s Ann M. Barwick Curator of American Art.\n\nhttps://seato
	day.6amcity.com/events/#/details/beyond-mysticism-the-modern-northwest/183
	08126/2026-04-16T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - All Events
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/beyond-mysticism-the-mode
	rn-northwest/18308126/2026-04-16T00
LOCATION:Seattle Art Museum\, 1300 First Avenue\, Seattle\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-all
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - All Events
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:BaOTWChEltK64IVTn0JYM
SUMMARY:TADAIMA: I'm Home
DTSTAMP:20260404T043959Z
DTSTART:20260416T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:After more than 80 years\, a treasured collection returns “home
	” to Seattle’s Japanese American community. In 1942 dozens of traditional 
	Boys’ and Girls’ Day dolls were entrusted to Bailey Gatzert Elementary Sch
	ool by Japanese American families facing forced incarceration. Most were n
	ever reclaimed after the war. Artist Miya Sukune uses recent research in M
	OHAI’s collection\, as well as interviews with Japanese American survivors
	 and their descendants\, to create an installation called “Tadaima\,” mean
	ing “I’m home.”\n\nTADAIMA: “I’m Home!” Bringing Seattle’s Girls’ and Boys
	’ Day Dolls Home reconnects the dolls with their traditional role of prote
	cting and blessing children. It invites visitors to celebrate the resilien
	ce\, memory\, and enduring traditions of the Japanese American Community.\
	n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/tadaima-i-m-home/18096356
	/2026-04-16T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - All Events
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/tadaima-i-m-home/18096356
	/2026-04-16T00
LOCATION:Museum of History and Industry\, 860 Terry Ave N\, Seattle\, Seatt
	le\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-all
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - All Events
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:HQW9SXpDp71hSL1Jbtdno
SUMMARY:Earth Month Event | Nature Journaling
DTSTAMP:20260404T043959Z
DTSTART:20260416T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:Nature Journaling in Pioneer Park\n\nIt's Earth Month! And to  
	celebrate we're hosting the first of our seasonal Nature Journaling educa 
	tional events. We will be exploring Pioneer Park with notebooks and pens m
	 aking observations about what we see. Participants will get instructions 
	o n how to begin nature journaling as well as a series of prompts to help 
	gu ide your observations.\n\nWhat is nature journaling? It is a practice i
	n  which you observe nature and spend some time crafting notes whether tha
	t' s words\, drawings\, painting\, quantitative data\, etc. \n\nClick here
	  to learn more: https://johnmuirlaws.com/nature-journaling-starting-growi
	ng /\n\nAll ages welcome\, no experience necessary.\n\nWhen: Thursday\, Ap
	ril 16th\, 10am-12pm\n\nWhere: Pioneer Park NW\, Meet at the corner of Isl
	and Crest Way and SE 68th St. Follow VOLUNTEER EVENT Signs\n\nWhat to brin
	g: Dr ess for the weather in comfortable clothes. Please bring a notebook\
	, and pens/pencils/water colors/crayons/etc \n\nRegistration: https://volu
	nteersig nup.org/J7KYK\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/ea
	rth-month-event-nature-journaling/18066409/2026-04-16T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday 
	- All Events
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/earth-month-event-nature-
	journaling/18066409/2026-04-16T00
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-all
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - All Events
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT2H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:Sj2KaOEiB--v5LMZ2zNC6
SUMMARY:Samantha Yun Wall: What We Leave Behind
DTSTAMP:20260404T043959Z
DTSTART:20260416T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:Samantha Yun Wall’s new paintings use overlapping silhouettes o
	f female figures as portals to unknown spaces and different temporal realm
	s. Impetus for the new body of work is a Korean folk tale in which the Pas
	que flower is symbolic of a grandmother who passed away without the loving
	 care of her grandchildren. It is a story of melancholy\, loss\, and remem
	brance. The delicate hair on the flower’s stem differentiates it\, and the
	 artist gives the plant a surreal aspect in some of her paintings\, replac
	ing the flower’s center with a watchful eye.\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.c
	om/events/#/details/samantha-yun-wall-what-we-leave-behind/18026187/2026-0
	4-16T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - All Events
